Britain anticipates an imminent statement from the IRA regarding a potential end to violence, following appeals from its political wing.
The 1998 Good Friday peace deal significantly reduced violence in Northern Ireland, but concerns remain about ongoing criminal activities by paramilitary groups.
Meetings between political leaders aim to maintain dialogue and address tensions during the Protestant marching season.
The US supports the peace process and urges the IRA to embrace democracy fully.
The potential disarmament of the IRA could lead to renewed cooperation between Catholic and Protestant factions, paving the way for lasting peace in Northern Ireland.
